<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-589-895  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 589 895.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 25 1990 n1237 p1(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Corrupt code caught down under. (Australia police track corruptinsider)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Collins, Tony.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ICL's Indepol, a corruption detection software program, is at thecenter of an investigation by the Queensland Police Department.andO;Detectives from the department had unsuspectingly approached ICLfor a database software that would help uncover information, suchas vehicle registration, bank account details, newspaper articles,and letters, but to their dismay ICL informed them that theQueensland Police already had such a software in their possession.andO;The detectives later discovered the Indepol software in thebasement of a former police department in its original package.andP;  Asource at the police department notes the possibility of thesoftware being hidden by corrupt officers.andP;  The source notes thatthe software, which has been lying unused for five years, may havebeen hidden by someone against the computer functioning andgathering intelligence.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   ICL PLC (Products).andO;Product:   Indepol (Computer program) (Usage).andO;Topic:     EthicsFraudAustraliaSecurity SoftwareLaw EnforcementInvestigations.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>